 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self-introduction): I prefer groove‑first, syncopated records with punchy, propulsive percussion, warm mid‑bass weight and analog mic character; baritone‑friendly, upfront lead vocals and stacked harmonies that function as rhythmic hooks; purposeful compression and analog‑style mastering that preserves headroom and transient punch; tight, radio‑length songs and single‑artist sequencing that reward repeat listens. I also lean toward Quincy‑style pop‑soul arranging — concise, hook‑first arrangements, bass and rhythm that lock, layered keys/guitars and lush strings that actively drive the groove — and mastering that keeps clarity and separation without over‑smoothing dynamics. Dislikes to avoid: diffuse/hushed restorations; mixes with over‑muscled low‑mids or crunchy midrange‑forward guitars pushing toward aggressive rock; brittle 1980s synth/cymbal harshness; scattershot multi‑artist compilations; and jangly, thin early‑60s pop with ragged vocal presentations.
Why Album‑centric Fleetwood Mac fits best: The Fleetwood Mac candidate explicitly promises a warm, low‑compression analogue sheen, tactile midrange and restored headroom — all direct matches for my preference for analog‑style mastering that preserves transients and mid‑bass weight without over‑smoothing dynamics. Its “spacious, vocal‑forward mixes” and “lush yet tasteful multitracked harmonies” align with my desire for upfront lead vocals and stacked harmonies that act as rhythmic hooks rather than sitting back as texture. The description calls out “restrained arrangements” and “cohesive start‑to‑finish sequencing” that preserve dynamics and transients — exactly the single‑artist, album‑first sequencing I prize because it rewards repeat listens and keeps arrangements concise and purposeful. Overall, the features emphasize preserved headroom, tactile midrange and an immersive front‑to‑back presentation, which minimize the diffuse/hushed restorations and over‑muscled low‑mid problems I dislike.
Why I rejected Turn It On Again — The Hits: On paper the Genesis hits anthology checks several boxes I like — “punchy, rhythm‑forward” mixes, tight bass and drums, preserved transients and inventive vocal layering — and its warm, analogue‑style mastering is attractive. However, it is a hits anthology spanning eras rather than a single cohesive album sequence. That moves it away from my preference for single‑artist, album‑centric sequencing that rewards repeat, start‑to‑finish listening; anthologies often feel scattershot even when limited to one artist. More importantly, Genesis’s catalog included a significant 1980s synth/drum/sound that can exhibit the brittle synth/cymbal timbre I explicitly dislike. While the remaster description tries to tame that, the anthology format makes encountering those 1980s textures and varied production styles much more likely across the tracklist. Given my strong preference for cohesive, vocal‑forward, analog‑sheened albums with restrained arrangements and consistent mid‑bass/punch, the Fleetwood Mac album‑centric release is the better fit.

